          "body": "Verses 13-17 are the chapter's theological abyss. Job has just named God's gifts — life, lovingkindness, care. Then verse 13 pivots with a single word: 'yet.' 'These things You have concealed in Your heart; I know that this is within You.' Job's claim is astonishing: God's chesed was a surface; beneath it was a hidden intention to watch for Job's sin and never acquit him. Whether Job is theologically correct here is the book's great suspended question — God never directly addresses this accusation. What we know is that the adversary, not God, proposed Job's testing (1:9-11), and that God's verdict in 42:7 is that Job spoke 'what is right' about God whereas the friends did not. The accusation of a hidden prosecutorial intention is Job's grief speaking beyond what he can prove — but it is grief rooted in real theological observation: the system of divine surveillance he describes in vv. 14-17 is the world he is actually experiencing."
