        "range": "10:1-2",
        "excerpt": "I loathe my own life; I will give full vent to my complaint; I will speak in the bitterness of my soul. I will say to God, 'Do not condemn me; Let me know why You contend with me.'",
        "body": "The opening two verses establish the chapter's entire register. Job does not speak *about* God; he speaks *to* God — and what he speaks is the rawest possible honest theology: I loathe my life, and I intend to tell You so. This decision is itself a theological statement. Calvin observed that the Psalms sanction lament as a form of prayer, that 'the Holy Spirit permits us to pour out our grief before God.' Job's chapter 10 is perhaps the Old Testament's most concentrated example of that permission being claimed.\n\nThe word *siach* (complaint, v. 1) is the same root used in Psalm 55:17 — David will 'complain and murmur.' It is prayer-vocabulary, not rebellion-vocabulary. Job is not departing from the tradition of honest covenant address; he is pushing it to its limit. The request of verse 2 is equally precise: 'Do not condemn me (*al-tarshe'eni*)' and 'let me know why You contend with me (*riv*).' The legal term *riv* frames the relationship as a lawsuit in progress. Job wants not to win the case — he knows he cannot (cf. 9:2-4) — but to understand what the charge is. Explanation, not acquittal, is what he is asking for.\n\nThis distinction matters canonically. Job is not demanding innocence; he is demanding intelligibility. The God he addresses is still his God — *Eloah*, the personal singular. Job has not turned to idols or to silence; he has turned to the only One who can answer. Peter Davids, writing on the James 5 use of Job as a patience-paradigm, notes that the tradition received Job as a man of faith precisely because he continued to address God through suffering rather than abandoning Him. The audacity of verse 2 is not faithlessness; it is faith at full stretch.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Siach* (complaint, v.1) — prayer-lament, from a root meaning to muse, meditate, or pour out. *Riv* (contend, v.2) — the legal term for a lawsuit or covenant dispute; used in Micah 6:2 of God's own covenant dispute with Israel. *Eloah* — the singular personal form of God, used 41 times in Job and only 15 times elsewhere in the entire Hebrew Bible, suggesting it belongs especially to the wisdom-lament tradition."
