        "excerpt": "Why then have You brought me out of the womb? Would that I had died and no eye had seen me! I should have been as though I had not been, carried from womb to tomb.",
        "body": "The chapter ends in the same place chapter 3 ended: Job wishing he had never been born. But the death-wish of chapter 10 carries a heavier freight than chapter 3's, because it comes after sustained argument rather than raw shock. Job has built his case, examined his creation, named God's hidden intention, catalogued the relentless hardship — and found no resolution. The death-wish of verses 18-19 is the logical terminus of an argument that has found no other exit.\n\nThe 'womb to tomb' compression of verse 19 is one of the Hebrew Bible's most economical expressions of despair. Job does not wish for a longer life with less suffering; he wishes for a shorter life — zero length, to be precise. 'Carried from womb to tomb' (*yaval* — transported, brought along) pictures a dead infant who passes from one darkness to another without ever having to experience the light. The logic is not suicidal; it is retrospective. Job cannot undo his birth, but he can name it as the original mistake.\n\nThe final petition of verses 20-22 is structurally significant because it abandons the formal direct address to God that has characterized vv. 2-19. Job shifts to third person ('Would *He* not let my few days alone?') — a sign that the argument has exhausted itself and only pleading remains. And the plea is minimal: not healing, not vindication, not answers — just 'a little cheer' (*balag*, a flash of brightness) before he goes to a land from which he will not return. The modesty of the final request is its own kind of pathos.\n\nThe darkness-catalogue of vv. 21-22 — *choshekh* (darkness), *tsalmavet* (shadow of death), *ephah* (utter darkness), *ophel* (thick darkness) — is four Hebrew words for darkness assembled as a destination. Sheol in the pre-resurrection horizon of the patriarchal wisdom tradition is not hell; it is the cessation of order, light, and relationship. The final clause — 'which shines as the darkness' — is the chapter's last and most hopeless image: even whatever light exists in that realm shines as darkness. There is no gradient from dark to light. It is darkness all the way down. The canonical reader, standing this side of John 11:25 and 1 Corinthians 15:20, feels the weight of what Job did not yet know.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Balag* (cheer, v.20) — to flash, to brighten briefly; used only here and Psalm 39:13 ('that I may smile again'). *Tsalmavet* (shadow of death, vv.21-22) — often translated 'deep shadow'; literally *tsalmaveth*, a compound of *tselem* (shadow, image) and *mavet* (death). Used famously in Psalm 23:4, where it is the valley through which the shepherd leads the sheep safely — a canonical counterpoint Job could not yet see."
